<BaseLayout
  title="How Toronto Restaurants Can Rank #1 on Google Maps in 2024 | TRG"
  description="Google Maps is the #1 discovery channel for local restaurants. Here's exactly how to claim your spot in the top 3 — from GBP optimization to review strategy."
>
  <Navbar />

  <main>

    <!-- HERO -->
    <section style="background: #1A1A1A; color: #fff; padding: 100px 24px 80px; text-align: center;">
      <div style="display: flex; justify-content: center; gap: 20px; margin-bottom: 20px; flex-wrap: wrap;">
        <span style="font-size: 12px; font-weight: 600; color: #E85D04; text-transform: uppercase; letter-spacing: 0.08em;">Google SEO</span>
        <span style="font-size: 12px; font-weight: 600; color: rgba(255,255,255,0.5); text-transform: uppercase; letter-spacing: 0.08em;">10 min read</span>
        <span style="font-size: 12px; font-weight: 600; color: rgba(255,255,255,0.5); text-transform: uppercase; letter-spacing: 0.08em;">March 2026</span>
      </div>
      <h1 style="font-family: 'DM Serif Display', Georgia, serif; font-size: clamp(28px, 4.5vw, 52px); line-height: 1.15; max-width: 780px; margin: 0 auto 24px; font-weight: 400;">
        How Toronto Restaurants Can Rank #1 on Google Maps in 2024
      </h1>
      <p style="font-size: 18px; color: rgba(255,255,255,0.72); max-width: 600px; margin: 0 auto; line-height: 1.7;">
        Google Maps is the number one discovery channel for local restaurants. Here's exactly how to claim your spot at the top.
      </p>
    </section>

    <!-- ARTICLE BODY -->
    <div style="background: #fff; color: #1A1A1A;">
      <div style="max-width: 720px; margin: 0 auto; padding: 64px 24px 80px;">

        <p style="font-size: 17px; line-height: 1.82; color: #2a2a2a; margin-bottom: 20px;">
          If you ask any marketing agency what the most valuable piece of real estate in the GTA restaurant market is, the honest answer isn't a billboard on the 401 or a prime location on King West. It's the top three results on Google Maps. Those three spots — what Google calls the "local pack" — receive 70% of all clicks when someone searches for a restaurant nearby. The restaurants ranking there aren't just getting more visibility. They're getting most of the customers.
        </p>

        <p style="font-size: 17px; line-height: 1.82; color: #2a2a2a; margin-bottom: 20px;">
          The good news: Google Maps ranking is not pay-to-play. Unlike Google Ads, where you're bidding against every competitor in your postal code, organic Maps ranking is earned through signals that any restaurant can build — with the right strategy. Here's exactly how to do it.
        </p>

        <h2 style="font-family: 'DM Serif Display', Georgia, serif; font-size: clamp(1.4rem, 3vw, 1.8rem); margin: 40px 0 16px;">How Google Decides Who Ranks in the Local Pack</h2>
        <p style="font-size: 17px; line-height: 1.82; color: #2a2a2a; margin-bottom: 20px;">
          Google's local ranking algorithm evaluates three primary factors: <strong>proximity</strong> (how close the restaurant is to the searcher), <strong>relevance</strong> (how well the business matches the search query), and <strong>prominence</strong> (how well-known and trusted the business is online). Proximity you can't control. Relevance and prominence are entirely optimizable.
        </p>

        <h2 style="font-family: 'DM Serif Display', Georgia, serif; font-size: clamp(1.4rem, 3vw, 1.8rem); margin: 40px 0 16px;">Step 1: Fully Optimize Your Google Business Profile</h2>
        <p style="font-size: 17px; line-height: 1.82; color: #2a2a2a; margin-bottom: 20px;">
          Your Google Business Profile (GBP) is the single most important ranking asset you have. Most restaurant owners claim their GBP and fill in the basics. Most don't finish. Here's what a fully optimized GBP looks like:
        </p>
        <ul style="margin: 0 0 24px 24px; color: #2a2a2a; font-size: 17px; line-height: 1.82;">
          <li style="margin-bottom: 12px;"><strong>Primary and secondary categories set correctly.</strong> Your primary category should be as specific as possible — "Halal Restaurant," "Seafood Restaurant," "South Indian Restaurant" — not just "Restaurant." Secondary categories add additional search coverage.</li>
          <li style="margin-bottom: 12px;"><strong>All attributes filled in.</strong> Halal, outdoor seating, parking available, accepts reservations, wheelchair accessible — every attribute is a potential filter someone uses to find you. If it's not marked, you're invisible to that search.</li>
          <li style="margin-bottom: 12px;"><strong>Menu uploaded directly.</strong> Not as a PDF link — as actual menu items in the GBP menu editor. Google indexes this content and uses it to match your listing to specific food searches.</li>
          <li style="margin-bottom: 12px;"><strong>Photos updated regularly.</strong> Google rewards active profiles. Upload new food photos, interior shots, and exterior photos at minimum monthly. Profiles with more photos receive significantly more views.</li>
          <li style="margin-bottom: 12px;"><strong>Hours accurate and updated.</strong> Including special hours for holidays. Incorrect hours destroy customer trust and trigger negative reviews — both of which hurt your ranking.</li>
        </ul>

        <h2 style="font-family: 'DM Serif Display', Georgia, serif; font-size: clamp(1.4rem, 3vw, 1.8rem); margin: 40px 0 16px;">Step 2: Post Weekly on Google Business Profile</h2>
        <p style="font-size: 17px; line-height: 1.82; color: #2a2a2a; margin-bottom: 20px;">
          Most restaurant owners don't know that your GBP has a built-in posting feature — similar to a social media feed that appears directly on your Maps listing. These Google Posts signal to the algorithm that your business is active and engaged. Post your weekly specials, limited-time menu items, events, and promotions. One post per week is the minimum. Two is better.
        </p>
        <p style="font-size: 17px; line-height: 1.82; color: #2a2a2a; margin-bottom: 20px;">
          Include local keywords naturally in your posts: "Our Brampton location is serving our weekend biryani special this Saturday..." Not keyword-stuffed — just genuine content that mentions your cuisine, your location, and what makes you specific.
        </p>

        <h2 style="font-family: 'DM Serif Display', Georgia, serif; font-size: clamp(1.4rem, 3vw, 1.8rem); margin: 40px 0 16px;">Step 3: Build Review Velocity — Not Just Volume</h2>
        <p style="font-size: 17px; line-height: 1.82; color: #2a2a2a; margin-bottom: 20px;">
          If you have 400 Google reviews but haven't received one in the past three months, you're losing ground to a competitor with 180 reviews that's getting 15 per month. Google's algorithm weights recency heavily. A restaurant generating reviews consistently signals that it's actively serving customers — which is the fundamental relevance signal.
        </p>
        <p style="font-size: 17px; line-height: 1.82; color: #2a2a2a; margin-bottom: 20px;">
          Build a systematic review generation process. At minimum: train your staff to ask happy customers for a review, place a QR code on every table that links directly to your Google review page, and follow up with a text message 2 hours after the dining experience. The restaurants doing this consistently are generating 20–40 reviews per month — and they're the ones ranking at the top.
        </p>

        <h2 style="font-family: 'DM Serif Display', Georgia, serif; font-size: clamp(1.4rem, 3vw, 1.8rem); margin: 40px 0 16px;">Step 4: Fix Your Local Citations</h2>
        <p style="font-size: 17px; line-height: 1.82; color: #2a2a2a; margin-bottom: 20px;">
          A "citation" is any mention of your restaurant's name, address, and phone number (NAP) across the web — Yelp, TripAdvisor, Zomato, Facebook, Apple Maps, YellowPages, and hundreds of other directories. Consistent NAP data across all of these directories is a foundational local SEO signal.
        </p>
        <p style="font-size: 17px; line-height: 1.82; color: #2a2a2a; margin-bottom: 20px;">
          The problem: most restaurants have inconsistent citations. "123 Main Street" on one directory, "123 Main St." on another, and a different phone number on a third. Google reconciles all of these signals and inconsistency creates confusion — which lowers your ranking. Audit every major directory, correct all inconsistencies, and add your listing to any major directories where you're missing.
        </p>

        <h2 style="font-family: 'DM Serif Display', Georgia, serif; font-size: clamp(1.4rem, 3vw, 1.8rem); margin: 40px 0 16px;">Step 5: Build a Website That Supports Your Maps Ranking</h2>
        <p style="font-size: 17px; line-height: 1.82; color: #2a2a2a; margin-bottom: 20px;">
          Your website and your Google Maps listing work together. Google uses your website's local signals — location-specific content, structured data markup (schema), and consistent NAP data matching your GBP — as relevance signals for your Maps ranking. A website with no location-specific content is a missed ranking opportunity.
        </p>
        <p style="font-size: 17px; line-height: 1.82; color: #2a2a2a; margin-bottom: 20px;">
          At minimum, your website should have a dedicated location page with your full address, neighbourhood context, what you serve, and why customers in your area should choose you. If you serve multiple neighbourhoods, build individual pages for each one. The more specific and relevant your content is to a searcher's location, the better your ranking.
        </p>

        <h2 style="font-family: 'DM Serif Display', Georgia, serif; font-size: clamp(1.4rem, 3vw, 1.8rem); margin: 40px 0 16px;">The Compound Effect</h2>
        <p style="font-size: 17px; line-height: 1.82; color: #2a2a2a; margin-bottom: 20px;">
          The restaurants that dominate Google Maps in Toronto aren't doing one thing well. They're doing all of these things simultaneously — and the signals compound over time. A fully optimized GBP, consistent review velocity, clean citations, and a strong local website creates a reinforcing loop where higher rankings lead to more customers, which leads to more reviews, which leads to even higher rankings.
        </p>
        <p style="font-size: 17px; line-height: 1.82; color: #2a2a2a; margin-bottom: 20px;">
          The restaurants not doing this are watching their competitors pull further ahead every month. If you're reading this and haven't audited your Google presence recently, start today. Every week you're not working on this is a week your competition is.
        </p>

